<font color="#FF0000">TO DOC</font><br>
<tt>Wed Apr 30 23:58:18 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Here is what you said as you discussed Kim Phuc that had Barry say to you  CAUTION DANGER AHEAD.<br><br>
&quot;To those M.P.'s and those photographers, I have very little to say other than may you burn in hell and suffer the ten time ten that those combined kids had suffered, on that day and all the days after. Barring the day you end up in hell, should I ever meet you, be assured that I will gut you from crotch to gullet like a fish.<br><br>
You responded:<br><br>
&quot;Oh, yea, by the way, the M.P.'s, Barry, don't forget the M.P.'s. And I said gut, Barry, not fillet. There is a distinct difference between gutting and filleting. I take it you don't fish. &quot;<br><br>
Barry was trying to tell you that you had crossed a line by making threats of bodily damage.  Are you a danger to the reporters, or the MPs.  If so, you are in trouble. If you aren't a danger....don't say things which can be interpreted to mean you are.<br><br>
Let me just remind you that two wrongs do not make a right.  I believe Kim Phuc would tell you the same. <br><br>
 As someone who may not go to church but still has a belief in a God , I go by the scripture &quot;Vengence is mine sayeth the Lord, I will repay&quot;.   I also believe the Buddhist teachings that what one puts out into the universe is what is returned to them. The reporters and MPs will get their due for their actions.   You can condemn the actions of others without crossing the line to vengence.  <br><br>
I appreciate the stories you are telling us of the Vietnamese even though they are depressing me no end.   It is oh so easy to think so much of ourselves and our pain that we don't see the pain of others around us. What you have shared are  family histories of Vietnamese who came to this country.    If we cannot or do not want to  listen to their stories,  maybe we can understand why our families may not want to hear about our experiences in that country.  <br><br>
Those of us who have had experiences with the Vietnamese understand how important their land, their deceased and living family are within the Vietnamese culture.  Doc, I think that  what you are trying to do here is to help others understand what the Vietnamese have had to endure.  Am I right?
<p><code>-- Decline to state  (Betty) </code><p>


